         <abstract>
            <p> The Maṣḥafa saʿātāt  is a version of the <title ref="LIT1961Mashaf">Maṣḥafa saʿātāt</title>, a Church service made up of psalms, biblical readings and hymns. 
               It includes the entire <title ref="LIT2701Dawit">Psalter</title> in its daily pensum.  Its witnesses "with no psalms at compline or in the midnight office, but with thirty psalms and three canticles in each of the other five hours" 
               <bibl>
                  <ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/> 
                  <citedRange unit="page">270</citedRange>
               </bibl> follow the Ethiopian distribution of the psalter.</p>
           <p>The three other types of Maṣḥafa saʿātāt identified by  <bibl>
                  <ptr target="bm:Taft1986Liturgy"/>
                  <citedRange unit="page">266</citedRange>
               </bibl> are: </p>
            <p> 
               <title ref="LIT2230Saatat"/>: the Coptic Saʿātāt;</p>
            <p> 
               <title ref="LIT3575Mashaf"/>: the Saʿātāt of <persName ref="PRS4709Giyorgis">Giyorgis of Saglā</persName>, 
               which replaced the <title ref="LIT2230Saatat"/>:  and is presently in use in Ethiopia and Eritrea;</p>
            <p>
               <title ref="LIT3577GizeS"/>: a cursus of prayers which is not really a Saʿātāt, but a Gize ṣalot for hermits and recluses.</p>
